0.body: Radium is a game engine built with Java and the LWJGL tools. The documentation will go over how to use the editor and all the tools, along with the scripting system. Radium is currently a fairly small project, only being worked on by one person. I do want the engine to grow to have most of the features modern day game engines should have, and all the tools necessary for creating a game. The whole engine is free and open source, so all features can stay free forever, never any payments. This also allows games to be distributed for free, without payment to Radium, making it great for all games.
0.title: Welcome To Radium!

1.body: There is no official installer or executable currently for Radium, making the only way to install it is to download the source code and compile it yourself. As of now, Radium is only available for Windows.
1.title: Installing Radium

10.body: The menu bar is the top bar of the editor. It contains features with project management, preferences, and hidden windows. The file tab is useful for project management. You can open scenes, save scenes, and even open your project in VSCode. The edit tab is used for your preferences. Change how your editor looks with themes. The Run tab is used for playing or stopping your scene. The Window tab is used for hidden windows. Hidden windows are windows that can be opened and closed.

22.body: There are a few small things that should be kept in mind when writing python with Radium. You should not use the import keyword for any Radium related imports. This is because it is not supported by Radium, and everything is already automatically imported. You cannot import other files you have written into your program. There might be a fix soon, but for now, everything must be contained inside one file. Do not edit any variables directly in a class. Instead use the dedicated getter and setter methods. And if there is no getter or setter method for the field, it should not be changed at all.
22.title: Radium Scripting Notes

Makes depth between 0 and 1 based on the near and far planes. Returns: float depth = getDepth();
return (2.0 * nearPlane * farPlane) / (farPlane + nearPlane - (depth * 2.0f - 1.0f) * (farPlane - nearPlane)); Return Type: float

5.body: There are really no good ways to currently run the engine. One way to run the engine is to open it in an IDE or editor such as IntelliJ IDEA or Eclipse. The second way is to build the project using gradle. Compiling the project with standard Java will fail because there are many dependencies handled by gradle.
5.title: Running Radium

6.body: There will be a bare bones project on Github very soon, and as soon as there is one, the docs will update. As of now, use Radium CLI to generate project files. After installing the CLI, make sure it is in your path. This article does a good job explaining how to do this. When this is finally setup, run the following command in the directory you want to the project to be in: radium create project-name This will create a project in the current directory with the name "project-name".
6.title: Creating a Project
